M|references|**Twitter/X-specific guidelines:**
M|references|- Conversational, casual tone
M|references|- Short sentences work best
M|references|- One clear message per tweet
M|references|- Hashtags: 1-2 max (0 is often better for ads)
M|references|- Threads can work for consideration-stage cnt
M|references|- **Spaces count** as characters on all platforms
M|references|- **Emojis** count as 1-2 characters depending on platform
M|references|- **Special characters** (|, &, etc.) count as 1 character
M|references|- **URLs** in body text count against limits
M|references|- **Dynamic keyword insertion** (`{KeyWord:default}`) can exceed limits — set safe defaults
M|references|- Always verify in the platform's ad preview before launching
M|references|When creating for multiple platforms simultaneously, start with the most restrictive format:
M|references|1. **Google Search headlines** (30 chars) — forces the tightest messaging
M|references|2. **Expand to Meta headlines** (40 chars) — add a word or two
M|references|3. **Expand to LinkedIn intro text** (150 chars) — add ctx and proof
M|references|4. **Expand to Meta primary text** (125+ chars) — full hook and value prop
M|references|This cascading approach ensures your core message works everywhere, then gets enriched for platforms that allow more space.